A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the falling highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that finds place in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every kilometre traveled and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing US roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups, calling for the government to use the small boxes to record the kilometres traveled – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax decisions.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
However, while one cannot agree in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently considering how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’ll only potentially use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the miles traveled among all Californian drivers in the state from 2025 onwards.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for this is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, funded from the taxes paid by Americans at the gasoline, is bankrupt.
In America, however, there is no longer as much fuel as it used to be.
Cars consume less fuel.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per litre) has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by one cent at high fuel prices.
“The fuel tax is simply not sustainable,” says Lee Munnich, an expert in traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
Its state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most long-term alternative,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, for example, the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way that traffic jams and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The Californian planners rely on the system in developing strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally established climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania’s Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most feasible long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation’s free marketers are also inspired by the idea of getting riders to pay for the journey.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s Vice President of Policies.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
Last year, the Senate approved a $90 million expensive pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of deputies from rural areas representing people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities are nevertheless moving on their own in this direction.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which currently hires 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mile fees instead of the oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers have recently been equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical about the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Consciousness about Big Brother and things like that was a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Earnings Management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult monitoring devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to capture the kilometres traveled, but not exactly when and where.
So, Khan said, the public would also be more calm.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not originally start to assist states in taxing motorists.
Instead, their goal was to set foot in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers should pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices it tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more likely to get involved if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programs have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners experiment with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they do not choose a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles travelled by all the inhabitants of the state.
Other organizations hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with less.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation, which can also be used to pay parking fees, insurance only needs to be paid for kilometres traveled, and speed data collected from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,” the city said in a planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
Officials told the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or annual fee could be imposed on drivers using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s Head of Legislation and Public Affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers are worried about their privacy and many other things.
