Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Distant planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been discovered by astronomers.
Whether there are lives on at least some of them, no one knows.
Selection is difficult: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering alien life?
These questions are just asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency Esa.
For their program "Cosmic Vision", they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that aim to decisively advance research.
The budget for such "L-missions" is approximately one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were discussed, five of which have now come to a closer election.
Numerous bodies reviewed the proposals, followed by the researchers.
In the coming days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Program Committee.
In total, Esa has chosen four major questions, to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision program, initiated in 2007, are to be answered.
What are the conditions for the emergence of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus also the formation of planets that orbit these stars – are still in proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
To address this question, in 2017, the space telescope "Cheops" will launch, which will explore 500 already known planetary systems in our surroundings.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
Using larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to be indicative of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question is also intended to ultimately provide an insight into the prerequisites for the emergence of life.
An important role plays the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined exemplarily.
With the "Solar Orbiter", Esa has already approved a M-Class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is expected to launch in 2017 and closely monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, Esa plans to be the first of the three L missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and explores the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and to investigate whether the laws of nature that we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under which all known natural laws can be united.
How was the universe created and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the common matter of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter whose gravity holds together galaxies and galaxy clusters, and dark energy which accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, the researchers do not know what physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are made of.
With "Euclid", the Esa has already approved a M mission here, whose launch is scheduled for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky, thus allowing conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
Many experts believe that the best chances of getting an L-Mission approval are "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do it, hope the scientists behind the project.
The mission includes a two- or three-sonde detector to be stationed in space.
In contrast to plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that emerged during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four more proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena" to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", the Earth.
Among other things, proposals for sample transport from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, and for solar physics, have already been excreted.
