What happens to my email on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was e-mail technically implemented in the design of the Internet service similar to the conventional post?
In the design of early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have failed to provide a stable foundation for a soundproof exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email corresponds more to an open postcard than to a sealed letter.
If the user "Anna" sends a mail to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna's email program or browser sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run through a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Will conventional emails be read along the way through the web?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The provider of the sender usually checks whether the mail includes a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
Furthermore, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail that will be deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Are unknown people also reading the emails?
The likelihood that unauthorized persons will read an email is extremely small.
Theoretically, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
The law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal possibilities to intercept or take notice of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With a high technical effort, it is also possible to disguise the metadata of an email communication so that it is not even easy to recognize who communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
