An interesting point is lost when repeating this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, made after the war, has fallen stuck.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Parties across the EU are gaining ground that are anti-EU or want to throw the euro over as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Party Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to win nearly five million votes in the September Bundestag election and thus effectively drive the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance against the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the forced jacket in which the respective national economy is forced by holding onto the common currency, many people believed that the project Europe had gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates, which are beneficial for German exporters – and that is what German politicians would like to do.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, Southern Europe will find itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – inspired by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deepening European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives prescribed by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry is paying twice as much for electricity as the United States and four times for gas.
This is a paralyzing cost disadvantage, as we could already see in Grangemouth.
All wage records in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt arises, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and lift Paris on the same level with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe for its own economic policy, which has to fight the distressed French economy.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-enemy Front National has just won a decisive re-election, hence referring the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of votes – a timely warning to the British Labour party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French workers?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency block in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and that is very well possible – then for the first time such a block could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point to which I want to go further: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and Southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Small-England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels where they can go.
I suspect that Scotland could drive very well in a looseer European association, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thinking countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise we should consider making Norway the same and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP administration in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity policy in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem Coalition had to blame for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to be forced on an austerity policy by Berlin and Brussels.
