Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the beginning of puberty, but it is “early” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, testing by an endycronologist could be indicated to avoid serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatment methods to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
Recommendations for medication or hormonal therapy are based on the child’s age, development speed, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is constrained in terms of medication, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioural problems and the feelings of girls unlike their elderly cousins.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how to handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter, at the age of ten, got her days.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many comprehensively published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are caused.
Boys are similar to girls in puberty.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study involving girls aged six to nine, which links body fat to entry into puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white older cousins.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, an early puberty seems to be influenced by all kinds of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and shame hair is growing earlier, the trend toward a full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as girls.
