Deposit houses boom in Singapore as crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a deposit house at the Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to be able to pay her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 in Singapore (about 1,730 euros) every month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
Indeed, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is rising – is so great that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, this week became the third deposit house listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Pledging jewelry is not only a fast way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, deposit houses in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just over the 15.4 percent required by the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, deposit houses offer the advantage that there is no need for creditworthiness verification or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
This is why millions of people in the region turn to bondhouses after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose financial policies in developed economies, lower- and medium-income families are looking for deposit houses to compensate for the difference in a stabbing economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the Agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which this week hardly came out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic gold prices peaks over the past two years have increased the trend of pledgeing personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the items pledged in the city state’s 200 bondhouses are gold.
People say, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai depository operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20% customer growth in its branches over the past few months.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the branch in Bendemeer and 15 more in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside of Asia, said Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company funds that with 60 percent of the $66 million Singapore it took this week with the Singapore stock market.
While some lenders have fallen into crossfire due to high interest rates, Yeah explains that depository houses not only lend cheaper interest than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
“Customers borrow items they already possess, and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase the household training,” she explains.
The deposit loan business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use deposit loans are in financial difficulty.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social layer come to us.
“This includes wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
