Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons manufacturing capability, a surveillance group said.
Syria has destroyed important chemical weapons and gas munitions production facilities, the global chemical weapons surveillance group said Thursday, while serious clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites allegedly stored toxic substances.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people have been killed since the start of the civil war three years ago.
The announcement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the date on
1 November, the Hague-based organization set Damascus to destroy or make all facilities for the manufacture of chemical weapons "inoperable", including all machines for the mixing of chemicals into poison gas and the filling of ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious schedule aimed at the destruction of all Syrian chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus must start destroying the existing weapons and supplies.
According to assumptions, there are about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility and deposits, according to the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which tracks the number of deaths in Syria through a network of activists, said on Thursday that 120,296 people were killed.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the side of the government, 29,954 of them belonged to the army of President Bashar Assad, 18,678 were government-friendly fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the death toll in the conflict at 100,000 since March 2011.
This number has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad’s troops have been fighting the rebels in Safira for weeks, many of whom have connections with al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not specify details.
The fighting underlines the danger to which chemical weapons inspectors are exposed, as their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic weapons arsenal is a race against time amidst a tumultuous civil war.
According to OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team “is now convinced that it has seen and witnessed all of the major production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria.”
Therefore, “no further inspection activities are currently planned.”
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 out of 23 of the sites indicated by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, it was not possible to visit two facilities, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites were abandoned, according to Syrian statements, and the chemical weapons program objects there were relocated to other facilities mentioned, which were inspected.
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved next month by the OPWC Executive Committee.
“I draw the hat of the bravery and courage you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization,” said Ahmed Uzumcu, Director General of the Surveillance Organization in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels in this civil war have been fighting against Assad’s government and their security forces, many members of the Alawites, a separation of Shia Islam.
In view of further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there was a strong explosion in an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion is not known, he said.
