FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but do not have cell phone calls)
Air travellers can now use their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, listening to music and watching movies from departure to landing, but not by phone, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
The airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight crew and the regulations for the storage of equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could soon approve the extended use of electronic devices,” the FAA said in a statement.
Passengers currently have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not re-start until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives green light.
On arrival, the passengers must turn them off again and not be allowed to take them off again before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on departure, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been refitted for the use of Wi-Fi at larger heights should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendant association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is safely implemented – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
We are honestly sorry to have to feel like watchers on this issue.
However, Internet connections for browsing, exchange of emails, text messages or downloading data less than three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority said.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still not “Words With Friends,” the scrabble-like online game actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave a jet from American Airlines publicly because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the climb.
And heavier devices such as laptops need to continue to be stored, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight also remain prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at landing and starting
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a safety expert on national transport issues, told CBS News that mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that air transmission can also disrupt broadcasting posts,” Rosenker said.
A industry advisory committee launched by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on use has increased.
Critics like Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
In 1966, the FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers after reports of interferences in navigation and communications devices by FM radios carried by passengers became known, which at the time represented the latest technological trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they don’t mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for a few years when flight height is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when you flip over.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are higher.
Among the advocates of easing the restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, employees of the company loaded a passenger aircraft full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but were unable to detect.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes that the interference with the equipment is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots talking about a disruption of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended the FAA to allow pilots to order the shutdown of the equipment by passengers when landing instruments under poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travelers who would now be equipped with extensive technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not contrary to safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
