Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA staff charged with accusations against Jonathan Lord for sexual offences
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with child-related sexual offences before accusations were brought against child caregivers Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, the Royal Commission for Sexual Abuse of Children reported.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA had stated that it “never had to do with an incident of sexual abuse of children in the organization.”
Managing Director Phillip Hare was inquired about a case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography and another in which a YMCA Caringbah Hall sports teacher was convicted of abuse of children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare said Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the Commission, knew of the first case but did not know the second.
He admitted that the YMCA’s declaration of opening to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that “there were external checks of the YMCA, in which the YMCA was recognized as the front line in child safety”.
Instead, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at YMCA at age 21, admitted that the management had failed to hire Lord "from me downwards" and did not ensure that employees had been clear about their obligations to report breaches of the child safety guidelines.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual offences against twelve boys during his two-year YMCA work.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare, however, denied that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented employees from reporting Lord’s violations regarding children’s safety.
The employees said they observed violations, among other things that Lord was alone with children, cared for them privately as a babysitter, let them sit on his lap, told one that he loved it, and let children play with his phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, said that Child Service Manager Jacqui Barnat, who was the supervisor of the Lords at YMCA Caringbah, “was very intimidating and most of the time very inappropriate.”
The managing director stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they would not have dared to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, rather, their friendship with Lord impaired their judgment, which is why they did not report him.
Hare stated that he had communicated his view to the Board of Directors of YMCA NSW that the lesson that the organization had to draw from the "Jonathan Lord" incident "does not concern the reporting" by employees, and that the Board of Directors had agreed to him.
Hare said the decision to urge employees to sign confidentiality obligations shortly after the allegations appeared was made by YMCA Child Services Managing Director Liam Whitley.
He said that it was to prevent contamination of evidence, but that was "over-eagerly" and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a child-safe organization at the time when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on sexual abuse of children, told the Commission.
He explained that there were "serious problems" with the recruitment, review, recruitment, training and supervision of employees.
The hearing was postponed until 20 December.
