Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people are forced into minibuses and drive to the villages in need of help with the laced medical equipment on the roof.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
They had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud more than once.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed as heroes: a feast, singing and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a reason to celebrate, and with its wide smile and boundless energy, it is happy to participate in the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins with the examination of hundreds of patients.
“Per ride we treat 500 people,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crickets, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school but many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anaesthetic.
The surgery usually takes place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operation and disinfection equipment is fed by the group’s generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning hours.
It’s an exhausting pensum, but village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference for the people they help.
One man explained that the free operation of a bowel rupture he had received now allowed him to return to work.
“It changes the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to his weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s asleep,” says Katie O’Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteering at Bwelles Group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be there in surgeries where we can help clump blood or hold the instruments Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and bring frequently donated medical equipment.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transportation and guidance.
“He’s without a doubt a hero,” says O’Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwell, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and fulfilling a promise he has given to his father is a great joy for him.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and learn how you can help.
