Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, below Cologne, a sewage duct from the Roman era is preserved.
Anyone visiting Cologne will not pass by the Cathedral.
Approximately 157 meters the two towers reach the sky and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two filigrane church towers know that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne Underworld.
Meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourism directly on the cathedral.
The tour begins incredibly unspectacular: “We start in the underground car park,” says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the town fathers wanted a car-right city, and therefore, from the remains of the old town wall, only what was not too large remained.
Therefore, most users of the car park rush past the Roman remnants today and only leave their car.
But whoever looks closer, discovers in Park Deck D2 an archaeological site separated by metal grating rods.
There are about five meters high ruins of handplate-sized stones to be seen.
"They are remnants of the Roman city walls built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look into a dark 15 meters deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly perceived.
The next stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants go down again to the depths.
Here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in German means as much as "City of Roman Law and City of the Agrippinens, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor cult".
And the pretorium is the former Governor's Palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the opening room of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewage channel, which is maintained here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can quietly walk a piece along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
There is still a surprise for Schulze.
After picking up the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16 meters deep, walkable shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground to reach the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins go back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will become part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction works are expected to begin soon.
However, there will be a few more years to complete.
