John Kerry says in an unprecedented acknowledgement that U.S. espionage has “gone too far inappropriately”
John Kerry, with an unexpected acknowledgement, suggested a defence of the US’ defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying that espionage in certain cases has “gone too far unreasonably.”
The Foreign Minister also admitted that he, together with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching on “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities were made public.
Due to the leaked information, the U.S. government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of outrage on the part of its allies.
Kerry said, “The president and I and others in the government have learned of some things that have almost expired by autopilot, simply because the ability to do so remained from the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, from September 11th.”
He was the first high-level member of the U.S. government to acknowledge that U.S. espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, “In some cases this has gone too far inappropriately.”
The President is determined to provide clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse occurs here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons in this process will not be affected.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a power of goodness and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added, “We are dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves into the air.”
“There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, exploding in the air and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to catch it and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented aircraft crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we learned about such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about the alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. on counter-terrorism efforts, as the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy from Connecticut said he had spoken with representatives of the European Parliament and others this week and is concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is very important for U.S. national security interests that Europeans remain on board in view of our joint efforts against terrorism,” Murphy, who serves as a Democrat in the Senate for the first time and is chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I am also going to Europe to make it clear that we have to continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their angry about the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have burdened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were incorrect and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other disclosures cited from documents passed on by Snowden that the NSA had monitored the cell phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of the national intelligence services, James Clapper, defended the espionage of allies as necessary, declaring that this is common on both sides.
In all the tumult, Murphy said his authority was preparing the Congress trip to be held this year, hoping that the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary was still being prepared.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the journey was to improve relationships, he also said that there would be some "serious words."
He said European governments must be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they have used themselves for years.
“While we can change our monitoring programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also agree with the fact that we are not the only ones spying,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is on a weekend trip to the Middle East and Poland to deal with resentment over US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran as well as US surveillance activities.
